ion": "RAR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9968999624252319, "span": {"begin": 817, "end": 820}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5914"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "RAR&alpha; protein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.957044780254364, "span": {"begin": 870, "end": 888}}, {"id": ["mesh:D065886"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "neurodevelopmental defects", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999133348464966, "span": {"begin": 944, "end": 970}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5914"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "RAR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9971318244934082, "span": {"begin": 1055, "end": 1058}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014212"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "atRA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9971066117286682, "span": {"begin": 1107, "end": 1111}}], "text": "Rara and Rarb are co-expressed in the developing mouse telencephalon, particularly in the corpus striatum, hippocampus and cortex (Ruberte et al., 1993; Yamagata et al., 1994), and exposure to retinoids during prenatal development can lead to microcephaly in humans (Lammer et al., 1985), rodents (Colakolu and K&uuml;kner, 2004; Shenefelt, 1972; Irving et al., 1986), zebrafish (Herrmann, 1995) and Xenopus (Durston et al., 1989). Furthermore, active transcriptional repression mediated by unligated RARs is necessary&nbsp;for correct specification of anterior structures, including the forebrain (Niederreither and Doll&eacute;, 2008). As evidenced by studies in Xenopus laevis, RAR activation during early neurodevelopment leads to anterior truncations. Expressing a dominant-negative co-repressor, which inhibits RAR-mediated transcriptional repression, or reducing RAR&alpha; protein with morpholino antisense oligonucleotides, results in neurodevelopmental defects that parallel those caused by excess RA (Koide et al., 2001).&nbsp;Later on, active RAR signalling instructs corticogenesis, through an atRA gradient secreted from the meninges (Siegenthaler et al., 2009).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:10:33 +0000 2026"}